Having determined the structure of the Bio-CDs, we next investigated their optical properties. The Bio-CDs showed a strong absorption peak at 285 nm and a shoulder peak at 320–500 nm (
                           Fig. S3
                        ), which were attributed to π-π* transitions of CC bonds and n-π* transitions of CO/CN bonds [50–53], respectively. The absorbance of the Bio-CDs intensified as their concentration increased (Fig. 2

                        a), demonstrating that Bio-CDs have adjustable capacity for light absorption in the purple to blue region of the spectrum. Photoluminescence spectra of solutions of Bio-CDs with different concentrations and at different excitation wavelengths showed that the emission of aqueous solutions of Bio-CDs was excitation-dependent (
                           Fig. S4
                        ), suggesting a capacity for step-by-step light conversion. Dilute solutions of Bio-CDs emitted blue fluorescence, whose intensity increased with increasing concentration over the range 0.01–0.1 mg/mL (Fig. 2
                        b). When the concentration reached 0.1 mg/mL, there was a small red shift in the emission wavelength, which could be related to the state of the surface of the carbon core. The excitation spectrum covers the absorption band at 335–415 nm (
                           Fig. S3
                        ), suggesting that the emission of the Bio-CDs solution can be attributed to transition of the surface state [54]. The photoluminescence quantum yield (PLQY) of Bio-CDs solutions was 10.1%. The decay curves of solutions of Bio-CDs can be fitted to a double-exponential function, indicating that the diverse fluorescent chromophores [55–57] or energy levels [42,58] present in the Bio-CDs are responsible for their multiple lifetimes. The lifetime of a 0.1 mg/mL solution of Bio-CDs (6.95 ns) was shorter than that of a 0.01 mg/mL solution (7.51 ns) (Fig. 2
                        c). This is attributed to aggregation of Bio-CDs monomers as the concentration increases, which provides a new energy level for the electronic structure. This increases the wavelength of fluorescence emission and shortens the fluorescence lifetime [42,58].
